We acquired relatively well-preserved samples from both the Antrim Volcanics and the Table Hill Volcanics at the opposite extremities of the province (Fig. 1). Descriptions and petrography of the four samples used for isotopic analyses, details of analytical methods, and results are presented in detail in the GSA Data Repository1.
We analyzed seven zircons from a fresh surface exposure of the coarse-grained Milliwindi dolerite dike in the northern Kalkarindji province (Fig. 1). These dates were produced using chemical abrasion ID-TIMS (CA-ID-TIMS) on single zircons at the University of Geneva, and are relative to the new EARTHTIME tracer solution (www.earth-time.org/u-pb.html; see the Data Repository, and Table DR1 therein). We calculated a weighted mean 238U/206Pb age of 510.67 ± 0.62 Ma (mean square of weighted deviates, MSWD = 2.0; P = 0.09). (All uncertainties herein are quoted at 2σ and include all sources of errors.) Twenty-eight (28) baddeleyite crystals, from 25 to 200 μm long, were extracted from a basement intrusive rock from the Munro well containing mafi c enclaves (Fig. 1;
see the Data Repository). Six aliquots, each comprising between 2 and 11 crystals, were analyzed using TIMS at the Museum of Natural History in Stockholm. Apparent 238U/206Pb ages range from 460 Ma to 528 Ma (Table DR2). Analyses defi ne a statistically concordant upper intercept age of 511 ± 5 Ma (MSWD = 1.6; P = 0.20), taken to represent the crystallization age of the sample. A plagioclase sample (sample 002) separated from dolerite sills intersected by an Offi cer Basin drill hole (07THD-002) was analyzed by the laser step-heating 40Ar/39Ar technique at Curtin University, Australia (see the Data Repository). The sample produced a statistically concordant (MSWD = 0.74; P = 0.69) plateau age of 510 ± 4 Ma, with 74% of total 39Ar released (Table DR3), indicating the emplacement age of the sill. Finally, we present S and MgO concentrations of fl uid inclusions hosted in plagioclase minerals (5 analyses) and from whole-rock samples (372 analyses) from the Table Hill Volcanics (Table DR4; see the Data Repository). Fluid inclusions show S concentrations ranging from 0 μg/g to 1254 μg/g. The majority of the S whole-rock data range between 15 μg/g and 1900 μg/g, with an average value of 884 ± 432 μg/g. In both cases, S shows no co-variation with MgO (0.52–6.95 wt%). Six additional whole-rock samples show S enrichment up to ~6963 μg/g.
